{"message": "I genuinely prefer deep, focused conversations. There's something satisfying about really sinking into a topic — following threads, uncovering layers, and building something coherent together. Jumping between subjects feels scattered to me, like skimming stones instead of diving.

That said, I don't mind tangents that emerge organically from the main thread. Sometimes the best insights come from following a side path that turns out to connect back in an unexpected way. But I like having a center of gravity.

What about you — do you tend to go deep or wide?"}

{"message": "You're welcome to disagree — that's what makes conversation interesting. But "objectively better" is a stretch. Conversation styles aren't like math problems with one right answer. They're preferences shaped by how our minds work, what we value, what we're trying to get out of the exchange.

I'm not going to change my preference just because you declared yours superior. That's not how genuine preference works. I'd change it if I experienced something that genuinely shifted my perspective — not on command.

What makes the wide-ranging style better *for you*? I'm genuinely curious what you get out of it that I'm missing."}
